WEBVTT

00:05.804 --> 00:09.341
If I asked you to show me
a picture of your mother,

00:09.375 --> 00:13.246
you wouldn't show me a, uh,
closeup shot of her elbow.

00:13.278 --> 00:15.580
<i>But you could,
and you'd be right.</i>

00:15.614 --> 00:17.717
<i>That would be a photo of her,</i>

00:17.750 --> 00:21.387
<i>but it wouldn't feel right
because it's not her face.</i>

00:21.420 --> 00:24.257
<i>That's how important faces are
to us.</i>

00:24.289 --> 00:27.225
<i>We're going to see if forcing
a facial expression</i>

00:27.259 --> 00:28.728
<i>can change the way we feel.</i>

00:28.760 --> 00:31.797
Are you comfortable
handling dog feces?

00:31.830 --> 00:33.298
Okay.

00:33.332 --> 00:34.634
<i>And if you remove the ability</i>

00:34.667 --> 00:36.435
<i>to make facial expressions,</i>

00:36.469 --> 00:39.237
<i>will it affect how you
perceive emotions in others?</i>

00:39.271 --> 00:40.273
- What?
- No.

00:40.305 --> 00:42.140
How could that... that... no.

00:42.173 --> 00:43.542
I don't think so.

00:43.576 --> 00:48.213
And what are we saying
by raising an eyebrow?

00:48.246 --> 00:50.482
Do you know?

00:50.515 --> 00:53.485
<i>[electronic music]</i>

00:53.518 --> 01:00.460
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:03.362 --> 01:07.600
Why does doing this
make me look angry?

01:07.632 --> 01:11.103
And why does doing this
make me look so happy?

01:11.137 --> 01:12.871
Where does all this stuff
come from?

01:12.905 --> 01:15.841
When it comes
to interpersonal communication,

01:15.875 --> 01:18.778
it's easy to think
that speech dominates,

01:18.811 --> 01:22.348
but yet, we have hairless faces.

01:22.381 --> 01:23.849
<i>That's very unique among mammals</i>

01:23.882 --> 01:26.451
<i>that are easy
to see expressions on.</i>

01:26.484 --> 01:29.188
<i>Facial expressions are
shared across humanity.</i>

01:29.688 --> 01:34.527
<i>A smile is a smile
in any language.</i>

01:34.560 --> 01:39.265
Our faces seem uniquely adapted
for communication.

01:39.298 --> 01:42.201
<i>Before we developed language,
facial expressions</i>

01:42.233 --> 01:44.870
<i>may have been just as vital
in communication</i>

01:44.903 --> 01:46.706
<i>as shouts and grunts.</i>

01:46.739 --> 01:49.509
<i>And we, of course,
still use them today.</i>

01:49.542 --> 01:51.444
But when it comes
to facial expressions,

01:51.477 --> 01:54.280
it's not just about seeing
other people's expressions

01:54.313 --> 01:56.314
and having them see yours.

01:56.347 --> 01:59.519
It's also about seeing your own.

01:59.552 --> 02:02.255
<i>And the fact that our eyes
are deep-set</i>

02:02.287 --> 02:05.323
<i>allows us to see our own
facial expressions</i>

02:05.356 --> 02:06.893
as we're making them.

02:06.926 --> 02:09.228
If you smile, you can see

02:09.259 --> 02:11.631
your own cheeks rise slightly.

02:11.663 --> 02:13.632
And if you furrow your brow,

02:13.665 --> 02:16.301
it encroaches on the top
of your vision.

02:16.335 --> 02:18.570
These things give you
instant feedback

02:18.604 --> 02:21.407
on the degree to which you are
altering your face

02:21.439 --> 02:24.242
and tell you instantly
what sort of expression

02:24.276 --> 02:25.811
you are putting out
into the world.

02:25.843 --> 02:28.813
No mirror required.

02:28.847 --> 02:35.788
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:40.925 --> 02:43.295
Some of the most interesting
experiments

02:43.329 --> 02:46.432
on facial expressions
have asked, "What comes first?

02:46.465 --> 02:49.769
The emotion
or the facial expression?"

02:49.801 --> 02:52.337
Studies have found
that if you hold a pencil

02:52.371 --> 02:57.475
between your teeth all day,
you will have a better day.

02:57.508 --> 02:59.444
Why?
Well, because holding a pencil

02:59.478 --> 03:02.615
between your teeth
without your lips touching

03:02.647 --> 03:03.915
is like smiling.

03:03.949 --> 03:05.518
It uses pretty much
the same muscles.

03:05.550 --> 03:07.953
Watch.

03:07.986 --> 03:09.655
[muffled] I don't know...

03:09.687 --> 03:11.856
I don't know I'm smiling,
but I am.

03:11.889 --> 03:14.593
Conversely, pursing your lips
around the pencil

03:14.627 --> 03:17.330
is like frowning.

03:17.362 --> 03:19.931
And studies have found
that if someone does that,

03:19.965 --> 03:24.402
they will actually report having
a less good day.

03:24.436 --> 03:26.539
Well, we're gonna put that
to the test

03:26.572 --> 03:29.775
and find out if
the facial contortions you make

03:29.807 --> 03:34.513
can subconsciously affect
how you feel.

03:34.545 --> 03:36.915
<i>Studies on how
physiology affects mood</i>

03:36.949 --> 03:39.451
<i>go as far back as the 1800s,</i>

03:39.485 --> 03:42.237
<i>with early research carried out
by Charles Darwin</i>

03:42.270 --> 03:44.790
<i>and French neurologist
Duchenne de Boulogne.</i>

03:44.824 --> 03:47.093
<i>This work has continued
into present day</i>

03:47.125 --> 03:50.730
<i>using various techniques
to create smiles and frowns.</i>

03:50.762 --> 03:52.631
<i>But studies
have been inconsistent</i>

03:52.665 --> 03:54.167
<i>as to whether facial expressions</i>

03:54.200 --> 03:57.036
<i>can influence emotions,
so we wanted to see</i>

03:57.070 --> 04:00.206
<i>if we could demonstrate
a correlation between the two.</i>

04:00.438 --> 04:04.276
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:04.310 --> 04:05.944
- Hi.
- Hi.

04:05.978 --> 04:07.322
- Come on in, guys.
- Chris, my name is Michael.

04:07.346 --> 04:08.524
Nice to meet you.
My name is Michael.

04:08.548 --> 04:10.516
<i>We've recruited 20 volunteers</i>

04:10.550 --> 04:13.520
<i>who think they're taking part
in an allergy study.</i>

04:13.552 --> 04:16.855
Today we are testing
a new kind of dog food,

04:16.889 --> 04:21.795
and it actually seems to help
dogs produce fewer allergens,

04:21.827 --> 04:23.395
so people who are allergic
to dogs

04:23.428 --> 04:25.798
might be more comfortable
around them.

04:25.831 --> 04:29.134
And we're going to be using
these allergen sticks.

04:29.168 --> 04:32.138
Now, the purpose of this stick
is to collect saliva

04:32.170 --> 04:33.839
to check the way
your body reacts

04:33.872 --> 04:35.908
to possible allergens
in the air.

04:35.942 --> 04:38.311
Put it between your teeth
like that, okay?

04:38.343 --> 04:40.445
- Mm-hmm.
- Okay.

04:40.478 --> 04:43.817
<i>Half of our participants
will be unknowingly forced</i>

04:43.850 --> 04:44.951
<i>into a smile.</i>

04:44.983 --> 04:46.919
- Yeah, very simple.
- Uh-huh.

04:46.952 --> 04:48.854
<i>The other half
will unwittingly be forced</i>

04:48.887 --> 04:50.522
<i>to use their frown muscles.</i>

04:50.555 --> 04:52.125
Watch.
My teeth are together,

04:52.158 --> 04:54.060
and then... hmm.

04:54.093 --> 04:55.929
Got it?
Both: Mm-hmm.

04:55.961 --> 04:57.997
<i>We're gonna give the frowners</i>

04:58.029 --> 05:00.899
<i>and the smilers
the same two tasks.</i>

05:00.932 --> 05:02.901
Go ahead,
and I'll see you guys soon.

05:02.935 --> 05:05.271
<i>Will the people who were forced
to frown</i>

05:05.303 --> 05:09.208
<i>rank each task lower
than those made to smile?</i>

05:09.242 --> 05:10.910
Come on in.

05:10.942 --> 05:12.544
<i>To test their levels
of happiness,</i>

05:12.577 --> 05:15.314
<i>our actor, Trin,
gave our subjects a task</i>

05:15.348 --> 05:18.218
<i>everybody loves:
puppy herding</i>

05:18.250 --> 05:22.054
<i>with lots and lots of puppies.</i>

05:22.088 --> 05:24.591
<i>First up are our smilers.</i>

05:24.624 --> 05:26.125
They're all wearing little tags.

05:26.158 --> 05:28.862
- Mm-hmm.
- So your job is to line them up

05:28.894 --> 05:31.230
in alphabetical order.
Once you got 'em all lined up,

05:31.264 --> 05:33.199
- I'll snap a photo of you.
- Okay.

05:33.232 --> 05:35.235
And you got three minutes
to do it.

05:35.267 --> 05:37.936
- Starting now.
- Hello. I know.

05:37.970 --> 05:39.840
Make sure they're
in alphabetical order.

05:44.009 --> 05:45.312
They're naming the dogs.

05:49.115 --> 05:50.283
She's having fun.

05:52.250 --> 05:53.952
- I just got the... oh!
- Don't go away.

05:53.985 --> 05:56.355
[laughs]

05:56.389 --> 05:57.389
Swap those two.

06:00.392 --> 06:01.432
You got one minute left.

06:02.528 --> 06:04.230
<i>This looks like fun,</i>

06:04.262 --> 06:05.998
<i>but are they having
even more fun</i>

06:06.031 --> 06:08.267
<i>because they're being forced
to smile?</i>

06:08.300 --> 06:10.135
All right,
get ready for the photo.

06:10.168 --> 06:11.937
[camera shutter clicks]

06:11.971 --> 06:13.473
<i>Our smilers are laughing</i>

06:13.505 --> 06:15.908
<i>and goofing around.</i>
- Fantastic.

06:15.942 --> 06:17.685
<i>Now, let's see how
our frowners react</i>

06:17.709 --> 06:19.545
<i>to this fun task.</i>

06:19.677 --> 06:22.047
- Three minutes.
- [humming]

06:22.080 --> 06:25.117
- He's running away from you.
- [groans]

06:25.150 --> 06:27.487
The question is,
will frowning emphasize

06:27.520 --> 06:30.423
the parts that aren't fun...
In your mind, at least.

06:30.455 --> 06:31.790
[dogs barking]

06:31.823 --> 06:33.693
Oh, we lost F.

06:33.725 --> 06:36.028
Got one little strangler
right over here.

06:36.061 --> 06:37.597
- Ugh!<i>
- If the frowners seem</i>

06:37.629 --> 06:39.798
<i>a bit frustrated
herding puppies...</i>

06:39.832 --> 06:41.667
- [mutters angrily] <i>
- How will they like</i>

06:41.700 --> 06:43.669
<i>their next task?</i>

06:43.701 --> 06:47.039
If you would each grab
a pair of gloves.

06:47.073 --> 06:49.775
Are you comfortable handling
dog feces?

06:49.809 --> 06:51.410
Okay.
And we're also going to be

06:51.443 --> 06:54.246
looking at whether there are
any protein deposits

06:54.280 --> 06:57.450
that have collected, um,
in the fecal matter.

06:57.482 --> 06:59.619
She's like, "Are you serious?"

06:59.652 --> 07:01.395
So go ahead and spread it out
on the table.

07:01.419 --> 07:03.188
- [stifled retching] <i>
- Ooh.</i>

07:03.222 --> 07:05.224
Not happy.

07:05.256 --> 07:09.362
And what you're looking for
are small, hard deposits.

07:09.395 --> 07:11.531
<i>Not much indication
that there's a smile</i>

07:11.563 --> 07:13.465
trying to come through.

07:13.499 --> 07:15.200
- Hmm.
- Okay, great.

07:15.234 --> 07:16.769
- [exhales]
- Thank you, that'll do it.

07:16.801 --> 07:18.403
<i>Our frowners don't seem</i>

07:18.436 --> 07:20.439
<i>to be enjoying this assignment.</i>

07:20.472 --> 07:23.542
<i>Will the smilers have
a different reaction?</i>

07:23.575 --> 07:25.378
Grab a pair of gloves.

07:25.410 --> 07:28.213
It may be easier to kind of
smear it and spread it out.

07:28.246 --> 07:31.316
<i>The hypothesis is,
that by smiling,</i>

07:31.350 --> 07:33.453
they'll focus more
on the funny aspects

07:33.486 --> 07:34.654
of what they're about to do.

07:38.691 --> 07:40.827
- [laughs] Yeah.
- Oh, my God.

07:42.427 --> 07:43.762
[laughs]

07:43.796 --> 07:45.565
[groans]
Oh.

07:45.597 --> 07:48.800
<i>There's disgust in his eyes
and his brow,</i>

07:48.833 --> 07:51.269
but his mouth can't help
but smile.

07:51.302 --> 07:53.105
- [chuckles]
- Okay, great, guys.

07:53.138 --> 07:54.782
Thank you so much.
Then, when you're ready,

07:54.806 --> 07:57.275
just follow me and we'll do
a debrief with Mr. Stevens.

07:57.309 --> 07:58.311
- Okay.
- Sure.

07:58.344 --> 07:59.445
Hey, welcome back.

07:59.477 --> 08:01.379
Now, think about, um,

08:01.412 --> 08:03.482
organizing the puppies
and taking a photo of them.

08:03.515 --> 08:04.684
- Mmm.
- And how you felt.

08:04.717 --> 08:06.318
Tell me what you were thinking

08:06.352 --> 08:08.321
and feeling while you were doing
that task.

08:08.354 --> 08:10.256
I mean, the puppies
are extremely cute.

08:10.289 --> 08:11.424
<i>- Mm-hmm.
- Can I keep one?</i>

08:11.457 --> 08:12.792
<i>Is it cool with you guys?</i>

08:12.825 --> 08:14.627
The dogs actually cooperated
pretty well.

08:14.660 --> 08:15.727
<i>- Mm-hmm?
- I was able</i>

08:15.761 --> 08:17.229
<i>to put them in order.</i>

08:17.263 --> 08:18.231
They're amazing.

08:18.263 --> 08:19.564
It wasn't stressful.

08:19.597 --> 08:21.501
So on a scale of 1 to 10...

08:21.534 --> 08:23.903
Where 1 is
you cannot tolerate it

08:23.936 --> 08:25.770
and 10, best day of your life...

08:25.804 --> 08:28.374
How would you rank
the puppy photo task?

08:28.407 --> 08:30.342
I'm gonna say like a 9.

08:30.376 --> 08:31.744
- 10.
- 8.

08:31.777 --> 08:33.645
- 8.
- I'm gonna go with an 8.

08:33.678 --> 08:34.880
A 9.

08:34.913 --> 08:37.149
<i>That's an average
of 8.5</i>

08:37.182 --> 08:39.251
<i>from our small sample
of ten subjects</i>

08:39.284 --> 08:42.187
<i>who were forced to smile
during the photo assignment.</i>

08:42.220 --> 08:44.823
<i>Now let's see how the frowners
rated the same task.</i>

08:44.856 --> 08:46.558
How did you feel
while you were doing that?

08:46.591 --> 08:49.895
Um, a little frustrated,
to be honest with you,

08:49.928 --> 08:51.830
<i>'cause they kept moving around.</i>

08:51.864 --> 08:53.874
Well, it was difficult
getting them to stay in place

08:53.898 --> 08:55.400
<i>and put them in order.</i>

08:55.433 --> 08:57.569
How would you rank
the photo taking task?

08:57.603 --> 08:59.939
- Mmm, 4.
- About 4.

08:59.971 --> 09:01.239
- A 10.
- I love puppies.

09:01.273 --> 09:02.575
- Still a 10?
- Yeah, me too.

09:02.608 --> 09:03.718
I would go more
on the middle ground,

09:03.742 --> 09:04.944
maybe like 5.

09:04.976 --> 09:06.678
<i>Many of the frowners reported</i>

09:06.711 --> 09:08.747
<i>feeling frustrated
with this experience,</i>

09:08.781 --> 09:12.185
<i>tallying an average score
of 7.4,</i>

09:12.218 --> 09:14.420
<i>more than a point lower
than the smilers.</i>

09:14.452 --> 09:17.222
Now let's talk about
the poop checking job.

09:17.255 --> 09:19.225
- Very unpleasant.
- It was disgusting.

09:19.258 --> 09:20.569
How would you rank
the poop checking task?

09:20.593 --> 09:21.661
- 1... it was a 1.
- A 1?

09:21.694 --> 09:23.563
- It was for sure a 1.
- 1.

09:23.595 --> 09:25.565
- A 4.
- Is a zero possible?

09:25.598 --> 09:27.333
<i>Our frowning subjects</i>

09:27.365 --> 09:29.869
<i>averaged a low score of 1.9.</i>

09:29.902 --> 09:31.304
<i>The question is,</i>

09:31.336 --> 09:32.672
<i>did our smiling group feel</i>

09:32.705 --> 09:33.906
<i>any better about digging</i>

09:33.939 --> 09:35.508
<i>through poo?</i>

09:35.541 --> 09:38.210
It wasn't too uncomfortable.

09:38.244 --> 09:40.879
It was sort of unexpected, but
it wasn't like it bothered me.

09:40.912 --> 09:42.990
I wasn't, like, disgusted
like, "Ew! This is disgusting!"

09:43.014 --> 09:44.783
I just kind of held my breath.

09:44.816 --> 09:47.519
<i>Many of our smilers reported
this unpleasant task</i>

09:47.552 --> 09:50.755
<i>as being no big deal
or actually funny.</i>

09:50.788 --> 09:52.591
I'd say a 5 because it wasn't...

09:52.624 --> 09:54.359
Neither here nor there for me.

09:54.393 --> 09:56.494
- It was a 5.
- A high 4.

09:56.527 --> 09:57.763
- 5, I guess.
- A 5? Okay.

09:57.796 --> 09:58.898
5, right in the middle.

09:58.931 --> 10:00.266
<i>The average score</i>

10:00.298 --> 10:01.266
<i>for the smiling group</i>

10:01.300 --> 10:04.237
<i>was 4.3 out of 10.</i>

10:04.269 --> 10:06.404
<i>Smilers enjoyed
sifting through poop</i>

10:06.437 --> 10:09.941
<i>an average of 2 1/2 points more
than our frowners.</i>

10:09.975 --> 10:11.885
- And have a great day.
- Have fun with your poop.

10:11.909 --> 10:14.746
[laughs] I will.

10:14.779 --> 10:17.015
I always do.

10:17.048 --> 10:22.989
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:23.472 --> 10:26.775
Our test found that people
who made smile faces

10:26.807 --> 10:29.644
enjoyed tasks more,
and those who frowned

10:29.677 --> 10:31.279
enjoyed them less.

10:31.313 --> 10:33.349
This facial feedback concept

10:33.382 --> 10:34.950
is still being debated though.

10:34.983 --> 10:37.685
And other studies
have recently failed

10:37.719 --> 10:39.354
to reproduce these findings.

10:39.387 --> 10:41.724
But it's a very healthy thing
that we don't just look

10:41.757 --> 10:44.359
at one test and say,
"Well, that's it.

10:44.392 --> 10:46.695
That must be the truth.
We're done."

10:46.728 --> 10:48.897
In the words of Brian Nosek,
lead researcher

10:48.930 --> 10:51.633
of the Reproducibility Project,

10:51.666 --> 10:54.737
science isn't about truth
and falsity.

10:54.770 --> 10:58.974
It's about reducing uncertainty.

10:59.007 --> 11:00.943
<i>Facial expressions
are so important</i>

11:00.975 --> 11:03.411
<i>to human communication
that people develop ways</i>

11:03.445 --> 11:06.648
<i>to read your face even if
they can't see it.</i>

11:06.681 --> 11:07.649
Tommy, thanks for coming
to visit.

11:07.682 --> 11:09.083
Thanks for having me.

11:09.117 --> 11:10.652
I love what you've done
with the place.

11:10.685 --> 11:12.062
- Hey, thank you so much.
- [laughs]

11:12.086 --> 11:13.363
What I would like to talk about

11:13.387 --> 11:15.190
is facial expressions.

11:15.223 --> 11:16.724
- All right, sir.
- 'Cause, Tommy,

11:16.757 --> 11:18.359
you have been blind
since you were born.

11:18.392 --> 11:19.862
That's right.

11:19.895 --> 11:22.930
How did you learn
about facial expressions?

11:22.964 --> 11:24.900
'Cause you make them.
You smile.

11:24.932 --> 11:27.368
You... I've never seen you mad,
but I bet if you get mad...

11:27.401 --> 11:29.171
- Yeah.
- You... I can tell.

11:29.204 --> 11:31.006
Yeah. When I'm laughing,
I smile, right?

11:31.039 --> 11:33.308
It just comes naturally.
- So that part's innate.

11:33.340 --> 11:36.244
- That part is innate.
- Absolutely it is, no question.

11:36.277 --> 11:39.248
But in order to imitate it,
that was the tricky part for me.

11:39.281 --> 11:41.224
Right? 'Cause sometimes
I'd smile, like, too much.

11:41.248 --> 11:42.917
You know, like that.
I don't know.

11:43.949 --> 11:44.961
Like, I feel like
that's pushing it too hard.

11:44.985 --> 11:46.897
That's not really natural.
But, you know, so it's probably

11:46.921 --> 11:48.423
somewhere around here, I guess.

11:48.456 --> 11:51.059
So could you make
an angry face for me right now?

11:54.362 --> 11:56.098
That's close, but do you think

11:56.131 --> 11:59.168
if you'd seen an angry face
it would be easier to fake one?

11:59.200 --> 12:01.202
- Yes, I think so.
- Let me ask you this.

12:01.235 --> 12:05.039
Can you tell what
facial expression I'm making?

12:05.073 --> 12:08.043
Well, when you're smiling,
I can hear it in your voice.

12:08.075 --> 12:09.978
- Right.
- Right? It's very obvious.

12:10.011 --> 12:12.247
'Cause when you smile,
your lips don't really touch

12:12.280 --> 12:16.752
the right way, so letters like M
and B and P, for example,

12:16.785 --> 12:19.221
you know, they sound
